elgian Revolution (1830-39) -- tCitizenship, Regionalization, and Identity. The Case of Alsatian Jewry, 1871-1914 -- tMoroccan Jewry and Decolonization. A Modern History of Collective Social Boundaries -- tContributors -- tIndex of Names and Places0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study explores the shifting boundaries and identities of historic and contemporary Jewish communities. The contributors assert that, geographically speaking, Jewish people rarely lived in ghettos and have never been confined within the borders of one nation or country. Whereas their places of residence may have remained the same for centuries, the countries and regimes that ruled over them were rarely as constant, and power struggles often led to the creation of new and divisive national borders. Taking a postmodern historical approach, the contributors seek to reexamine Jewish history and Jewish studies through the lens of borders and boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJewsvCongresses. 0aJewsxIdentityvCongresses. 4aCLH. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aJUD. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh1 aBrasz, Chaya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaelen, Veerle Vanden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco, Manuela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrishman, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFrishman, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaan, Ido, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHofmeester, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyman, Paula E., econtributor.4ctb